body:
**Describe the bug**
The following example test has a huge performance overhead when using a reporter derived from CumulativeReporterBase (junit, sonarqube), even when successful tests aren't being reported.

```
#define CATCH_CONFIG_MAIN
#include <catch2/catch.hpp>

// other reporters
#include <catch2/catch_reporter_automake.hpp>
#include <catch2/catch_reporter_sonarqube.hpp>
#include <catch2/catch_reporter_tap.hpp>
#include <catch2/catch_reporter_teamcity.hpp>

#include <vector>

namespace
{
    constexpr const std::size_t LARGE_BUFFER_SIZE { 32 * 1024 * 1024 }; // 32MB
    using u_byte = unsigned char;
    std::vector<u_byte> generateLargeBuffer()
    {
        std::vector<u_byte> buffer( LARGE_BUFFER_SIZE );
        return buffer;
    }
}// namespace

TEST_CASE( "REQUIRE() 2 large vectors of bytes are equal" )
{
    auto buffer1 { generateLargeBuffer() };
    auto buffer2 { generateLargeBuffer() };

    // will take ~30s with junit/sonarqube reporter, but fractions of a second on other reporters
    REQUIRE( buffer1 == buffer2 );
}

```
I traced it down to the following call chain:
```
CumulativeReporterBase::assertionEnded()
  prepareExpandedExpression()
    AssertionResult::getExpandedExpression()
      AssertionResultData::reconstructExpression()
```

```
    std::string AssertionResultData::reconstructExpression() const {

        if( reconstructedExpression.empty() ) {
            if( lazyExpression ) {
                ReusableStringStream rss;
                rss << lazyExpression; // <- most of the time is spent in operator<<
                reconstructedExpression = rss.str();
            }
        }
        return reconstructedExpression;
    }
```

The xml reporter *does* take the performance hit if successful tests are reported (-s option), and that does show how silly the expansion of this expression is.

**Expected behavior**
Using the junit reporter should have similar performance as the xml reporter when successful results aren't being shown, especially when considering that `utest -r junit -s` doesn't display the expanded expression.

**Reproduction steps**
Steps to reproduce the bug.
<!-- Usually this means a small and self-contained piece of code that uses Catch and specifying compiler flags if relevant. -->

Run the provided test with `-r junit` and `-r xml` and observe the difference.

**Platform information:**
<!-- Fill in any extra information that might be important for your issue. -->
 - OS: **Linux**
 - Compiler+version: **GCC v10.1**
 - Catch version: **v2.12.1**

**Addtional Note**
It seems incorrect to me that the junit reporter would include the reporter's processing time in the unit test time:
```
workspace/catch2junitslowdowntest/cmake-build-debug 
❯ time ./bin/utest -r junit
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<testsuites>
  <testsuite name="utest" errors="0" failures="0" tests="1" hostname="tbd" time="32.9809" timestamp="2020-06-21T04:46:41Z">
    <testcase classname="utest.global" name="REQUIRE() 2 large vectors of bytes are equal" time="32.980824"/>
    <system-out/>
    <system-err/>
  </testsuite>
</testsuites>

real	0m33.012s
user	0m32.453s
sys	0m0.523s
```

Actually running the unit test's code is a small fraction of the time spent, comparing against the xml reporter's time:
```
workspace/catch2junitslowdowntest/cmake-build-debug 
❯ time ./bin/utest -r xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<Catch name="utest">
  <Group name="utest">
    <TestCase name="REQUIRE() 2 large vectors of bytes are equal" filename="/home/joe/workspace/catch2junitslowdowntest/main.cpp" line="23">
      <OverallResult success="true"/>
    </TestCase>
    <OverallResults successes="1" failures="0" expectedFailures="0"/>
  </Group>
  <OverallResults successes="1" failures="0" expectedFailures="0"/>
</Catch>

real	0m0.043s
user	0m0.018s
sys	0m0.025s
```
